    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-03-16T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-03-16T09:00:00-05:00" n="51"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d51">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 51</seg>
                </opener>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">850.33/3–1651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Liaison and Political Reports
                            Division</gloss> to the Office of the <gloss type="to">United States
                            High Commissioner for Germany</gloss>, at Frankfurt</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d51fn1">Repeated to London, Paris, and the Department of
                        State, which is the source text.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bonn</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-03-16T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 16, 1951—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>756. From Liaison Bonn. During conversation March 16, Dr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_SK1">Schumacher</persName> termed US support of <persName
                        corresp="#p_SR1">Schuman</persName> Plan part of a Franco-American
                    conspiracy against Ger workers. He said there can be no talk of equality as long
                    as the Ger economy is expected to support the artificially over-expanded Fr
                    steel industry. The <gloss target="#t_SPD1">SPD</gloss> leader also again
                    attacked <persName corresp="#p_SR1">Schuman</persName> Plan as unconcealed Fr
                    attempt to gain control of Ger industry. (See Bonn’s tel 419 to Frankfort, rptd
                    Dept 373, Paris 85, Dec 7.<note n="2" xml:id="d51fn2">Not printed.</note>) He
                    said his party was seething over latest results in <persName corresp="#p_SR1"
                        >Schuman</persName> plan negots and referred to agrmt to liquidate <gloss
                        target="#t_DKV1">DKV</gloss> by 1952 as an act which is bound to result in
                    unemployment, possible unrest and a lower living standard for the miners of the
                    Ruhr. <persName corresp="#p_SK1">Schumacher</persName> stated emphatically that
                    his party wld never approve the <persName corresp="#p_SR1">Schuman</persName>
                    Plan in its present form and that it wld launch a determined campaign against
                    its ratification. This opposition cld well lead to what he called “a new
                    relationship between the occupation powers and Ger labor”. <persName
                        corresp="#p_SK1">Schumacher</persName> concluded his remarks by saying that
                    there eld be no Ger military contribution as long as Allies continue to sponsor
                    such projects of inequality as the <persName corresp="#p_SR1">Schuman</persName>
                    and <persName corresp="#p_PR2">Pleven</persName> Plans.</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_SPD1">SPD</gloss> leader made similar remarks to
                        <persName>Joseph Alsop</persName>, US journalist, during interview on Mar
                    15, further stating that shld communism ever be reborn in Germany, the Americans
                    can take credit for having acted as godfather by sponsoring <persName
                        corresp="#p_SR1">Schuman</persName> Plan.</p>
                <p>Liaison Bonn believes that the violence of <persName corresp="#p_SK1"
                        >Schumacher</persName>’s opposition to <persName corresp="#p_SR1"
                        >Schuman</persName> Plan is at least partially due to his anxiety over
                    somewhat doubtful trade union support of his party’s position. Impression was
                    gained that <gloss target="#t_SPD1">SPD</gloss> leader is determined to use all
                    available means to rally labor opposition to <persName corresp="#p_SR1"
                        >Schuman</persName> Plan in order to prevent workers from slipping out of
                        <gloss target="#t_SPD1">SPD</gloss>’s grasp. [Liaison Bonn.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MJJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McCloy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
